	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Difficulties faced in Pan Caribbean’s Jamaican operations </h1>

			
			<h4>
												20 October 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to Jamaica’s Minister of Agriculture, Roger Clarke, production at the Pan Caribbean Sugar Company’s (Pan Caribbean’s) three factories, which account for 70% of Jamaica’s sugar production capacity, is falling. Mr Clarke reported in August that total projected sugar production in 2013 “is 125,000 tonnes compared to 131,589” in 2012, with the Pan Caribbean factories projected to produce 54,000 tonnes, compared 65,000 tonnes in 2012. This falls far short of the objective – of 150,000 tonnes of sugar production by 2014 – set at the time of the sale of the government-owned estates and factories. Mr Clarke commented that “clearly, there are some deficiencies within the Complant operations,” but reiterated the government’s commitment of “assisting Pan Caribbean to reach its target”. Pan Caribbean is owned by the Chinese company Complant.</p><p>Press reports from Jamaica indicate that industrial action could affect the Jamaican sugar sector if 132 security guards who have been placed on “discretionary leave” since July 2013 are not reinstated. Since Pan Caribbean took over the government estates and factories in August 2011, 400 workers have been laid off. Pan Caribbean claims that the lay-offs form part of a necessary process of restructuring to automate certain processes and reduce costs.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Jamaica Observer</i>, ‘Sugar impasse threatens sector's recovery’, 19 August 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/Sugar-impasse-threatens-sector-s-recovery_14908608" target="_self">http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/Sugar-impasse-threatens-sector-s-rec...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Given the importance of Pan Caribbean’s sugar production to overall Jamaican sugar production capacity (70%), the company’s performance has a major bearing on national sugar production. The decline of around 11,000 tonnes in Pan Caribbean’s sugar production masked the improved performance of other Jamaican sugar companies, with overall Jamaican sugar production only declining by 6,590 tonnes. In 2013, Pan Caribbean’s projected contribution to national sugar production will fall to 36%, from 43% in 2012.</p><p>The diverse performance of individual companies, together with annual fluctuations, serves to highlight the underlying problems of competitiveness facing the Jamaican sugar sector. Cost efficiency in sugar production is closely linked to economies of scale and underlying productivity gains. In terms of productivity gains, Pan Caribbean’s process of restructuring clearly needs to be accelerated if the expectations of production expansion are to be realised. This requires labour restructuring to be complemented by investments in modern plant and processing technology.</p><p>To date, it appears that Pan Caribbean has not yet made the necessary investments to scale up its capacity utilisation, expand its productivity and show a clear long-term return for the current difficult process of labour restructuring. While the Jamaican government remains committed to supporting Pan Caribbean in developing sugar production, a clearly defined time line for modernisation and productivity improvement appears to be needed if the policy concessions made by government in conceding the right for Pan Caribbean’s to directly market its own sugar are to be justified (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Sugar/New-marketing-agency-agreement-signed-with-PCSC-in-Jamaica" target="_blank">New marketing agency agreement signed with PCSC in Jamaica</a>’, 18 June 2012).</p>
		</div>
		
